article.headline: Arkansas 85, Jacksonville 65
article.story: NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Jonathan Modica's fast start has a lot to do with Arkansas improving to 3-0 for the first time since 1998. The sophomore guard led the Razorbacks in scoring for the third straight game with 23 points in an 85-65 victory over Jacksonville on Saturday and he's making his shots count. In averaging 23 points per game, he's shooting 72 percent from the field (26 of 36) and 92 percent from the line (12 of 13) this season. "I'm just trying to take decent shots," said Modica, who made 10 of 13 shots on Saturday. "I'm not doing anything too different. Last year, I took a lot of 3s and now I'm trying to drive to create open shots." Arkansas coach Stan Heath said Modica is more comfortable this year than last, when he led the Razorbacks at just 11.5 points per game. "He's really getting into a flow," Heath said. "He has a knack for scoring in a lot of different ways. Today, you mostly saw him attack the basket and mostly get things done inside. "He's been the pillar so far as we start the season and we need that." Arkansas used a 13-0 run at the start of the second half to secure the victory. Kendrick Davis made two 3-pointers and Billy Pharis made one to push the lead from seven points to 44-28. "In the second half, they doubled the lead in about the first three or four trips down the floor and we just didn't recover," Jacksonville coach Hugh Durham said. Davis, who added 19 points, had eight points during the run and the Razorbacks pushed the lead to 20 before Jacksonville (1-2) made a bid to stay in the game by making four 3-pointers. "Coach just told us to come out and play hard and we did," Davis said. Arkansas has never trailed in victories over Nicholls State, Grambling State and Jacksonville. Leading 67-54, Modica put the Dolphins away with eight points in a 13-5 run. The Razorbacks started 1-4 in Heath's first season, which finished at 9-19. This Arkansas team is building confidence heading into Wednesday's game against Oral Roberts, a team that beat the Razorbacks last year. "It feels a whole lot better than being 1-2 right now," Modica said. "We're just happy about having a winning mindset. When you go to practice and you have confidence and there's no animosity between anybody." Modica picked up his second 20-point game of the season. The sophomore only had two 20-point games as a freshman. It's the second game in row that a slow second-half start kept Jacksonville from challenging for an upset on the road. Jacksonville trailed North Carolina-Wilmington, an NCAA Tournament team last year, by six at halftime on Monday before falling 71-53. Jacksonville scored just two points in the first 7:41 of that loss and it went three minutes before Haminn Quaintance hit a 3-pointer to snap Arkansas' 13-0 run. After making 44 percent of their shots in the first half, the Razorbacks made 20 of 34 in the second half to finish the game at 52 percent. "I told coach Heath if they shoot the ball like that all year, they'll win a lot of games," Durham said. Quaintance and Jared Stockton led the Dolphins with 12 points. Aubrey Conerly had 10 points and 10 assists. The Dolphins, who entered the game averaging 22 turnovers a game, made 24 against Arkansas. Sophomore Eric Ferguson made his first start at point guard after coming off the bench in the first two games. However, he picked up this third foul with 9:39 left in the first half and sat until the second half. Jacksonville trimmed the lead to 20-14 when Conerly converted the free throws following Ferguson's third foul. Diallo's offensive putback cut the lead to four 30 seconds later. Arkansas pushed the lead back to 10 on several occasions before the half, but Conerly hit two 3-pointers to cut the halftime deficit to 35-28. The Razorbacks took their biggest lead of the first half at 18-6 thanks to five offensive rebounds in the first five minutes. Grambling State held them to six offensive rebounds for the entire game on Tuesday. Arkansas finished with 13 for the game, but it wasn't the only improved statistic. The Razorbacks had more assists, 22, than turnovers, 15, for the first time in Heath's tenure. Freshman Ronnie Brewer, who had 12 points, led the team with seven assists. Davis had four assists and no turnovers. "We strive to share the ball," Heath said. "We had a lot of guys touching the ball today and it showed in the assists we had."
